text.text:
When I moved to London in October of last year, I found this gem when looking for a gym in my area. I had never done martial arts before and worried that doing something so different to my previous disciplines (swimming, rowing, triathlons) would be intimidating and unfruitful, but I found Professor Oliveira, as well as the whole group, to be supportive, passionate, and welcoming. BJJ is nothing to take lightly, so expect to be humbled and called out if you're slacking, but I highly recommend giving it a go if you've never done it before. This gym is genuinely one of the reasons that I settled so comfortably into London, as it gave me a community.

If you are a woman that is looking for a BJJ gym, just know that there are few other women at the club and that other clubs in London may be better suited if the ratio of men to women is important to you, but Professor Oliveira is very attentive in making sure the men treat you with respect and care. This is very much a smaller gym than others I've encountered in London, meaning that the timetable is more limited, but if the schedule works with your lifestyle, you'll find the membership is one of the best in regards to pricing in London.

Oss :)

I've been attending this gym for two months now and this is a review I would like to read two months ago when I was looking for any information about the gym.

About me. I'm a white belt with two stripes. This is my second BJJ gym. The previous one I was attending for two years (not always regularly). Due to a house move, I needed to find a new gym here. I googled and I found ACTJJ UK school, fairly close (10mi.) and matched in general what I was looking for - a traditional Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu gym. I contacted Luciano on Facebook and a week later I was attending the first class.

Luciano Junior, the head coach, is a Brazilian black belt, who runs ACTJJ UK. He is a humble, positive guy. It's his sole effort, that makes the gym what it is now - a good and a quality traditional BJJ gym. Luciano is a black belt under Alessandro Xaruto 4th degree black belt, who runs ACTJJ in Brazil.

At the moment there are BJJ classes and a few types of fitness/crossfit classes. I haven't tried these fitness/crossfit classes, but I've seen a few videos and they look amazing. The BJJ classes have a typical structure: warmup, techniques and sparring matches, if there is enough time. In terms of types of BJJ classes, there are classes for beginners, advanced and mixed. All are with Gi, at the moment there are no no-Gi classes. One thing related to the class structure I like is that every class during warmup Luciano matches people, so they don't randomly pair themselves.
